 
<p>

Discovery of a <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/apr/18/scientists-discover-pristine-deep-sea-galapagos-reef-teeming-with-life">thriving coral reef that is too deep for ordinary
    diving</a> leads some to hope these species will not be wiped out by heat.
<p>
However, heat is not the only threat to marine life.  Too much CO2 in
the sea will kill all coral, and many other kinds of animals, by
<a href="https://stallman.org/archives/2011-may-aug.html#30_May_2011_(Acidification)">making the ocean too acidic for them</a>.
<p>
We need to cut the CO2 emissions even if it isn't too hot.

 